& [Inference] is bounded and restrained
  + [primary_observation] is T = c*log(x) is a cleaner coordinate law than fixed T because T/log(x) is held equal to c across samples
  + [coordinate_result] is scale-tied T improves average residual structure and strengthens sharp as a finite baseline, but does not stabilize the whole residual surface
  + [window_observation] is sharp dominates win count and average residual, while Fejer, Lanczos, and Hann still win local pockets
  + [multiplier_observation] is c32 gives the best average residual, but best local c drifts by x, especially at x=500, x=800, and x=1000
  + [bridge_result] is the scale-tied log atlas still does not justify another explicit/Euler bridge as a single coupled identity track
  + [next_reasonable_coordinate] is compare multiple declared scale laws, rather than increasing smoothing policy complexity; candidates include T = c*log(x), T = c*sqrt(x), and T = c*sqrt(x)*log(x) only as bounded diagnostic laws
  + [answered_question] is yes, T = c*log(x) should be retained as a cleaner diagnostic coordinate than fixed T, but no, it is not sufficient as a final stabilizing identity

  = must: treat the atlas as finite residual sensitivity and coordinate-law diagnosis only
  = must: keep scale-tied T separate from fixed T and raw zero-pair count
  = must: treat c32 average strength and x=100/x=200 stability as local finite observations, not theorem signals
  = must: require a new source-defined scale-law comparison before testing other x-dependent laws
  - never: claim RH proof, disproof, independent zero certification, critical-line authority, universal cutoff-law superiority, or explicit/Euler bridge identity from this atlas

